Saving it:

Scaled <- scale(dataToCluster)

Now they all have similar range:

boxplot(Scaled,horizontal = T, las=2,cex.axis=0.4)

Setting random seed and computing distance matrix:

set.seed(999)

library(cluster)
## Warning: package 'cluster' was built under R version 4.1.1
Scaled_DM=daisy(x=Scaled, metric = "gower")

Using function fviz_nbclust to see the optimal number of clusters:

library(factoextra)

For hierarchical (agglomerative):

fviz_nbclust(Scaled, 
             hcut,
             diss=Scaled_DM,
             method = "gap_stat",
             k.max = 10,
             verbose = F,
             hc_func = "agnes")

fviz_nbclust(Scaled, 
             hcut,
             diss=Scaled_DM,
             method = "gap_stat",
             k.max = 10,
             verbose = F,
             hc_func = "diana")

They all show 1 as the optimal number, however I will go ahead and set 4 clusters:

NumberOfClusters=4

#Partitioning (pam):
res.pam = pam(x=Scaled_DM,
              k = NumberOfClusters,
              cluster.only = F)

#Hierarchical - agglomerative (agnes):

res.agnes= hcut(Scaled_DM, 
                k = NumberOfClusters,
                isdiss=TRUE,
                hc_func='agnes',
                hc_method = "ward.D2")

#Hierarchical - divisive (diana):
res.diana= hcut(Scaled_DM, 
                k = NumberOfClusters,
                isdiss=TRUE,
                hc_func='diana',
                hc_method = "ward.D2")

Now I will add the results to the dataframe (fromPy). This will add new variables to the original dataframe that will tell me which country is in which cluster:

fromPy$pam=as.factor(res.pam$clustering)
fromPy$agn=as.factor(res.agnes$cluster)
fromPy$dia=as.factor(res.diana$cluster)

Now, I will plot the silhouettes, starting with pam:

Pam (partitioning) and Diana (hierarchical - divisive) do a better job than Agnes (hierarchical - agglomerative) as their average silhouette width is higher (0.38 vs. 0.36).

So, the best way to cluster is either partitioning or hierarhical - divisive. Let’s take a look at the badly clustered cases:

Regression:

I want to use regression to see the relationship between the contribution of the service sector to total GDP and the total CO2 emissions.

The dataset is already loaded, let’s verify it:

str(fromPy, width = 70,strict.width='cut')

I will be using the explanatory approach.

Hypothesis 1: CO2 emissions increase as the total GDP goes up.(Dependent variable: CO2x1000, independent variable: TotalGDPinMillions)

hypo1=formula(CO2x1000~ TotalGDPinMillions)

Hypothesis 2: CO2 emissions increase as the total GDP and the population go up.*

hypo2=formula(CO2x1000~ TotalGDPinMillions + Population)

Computing regression models:

gauss1=glm(hypo1,
           data = fromPy,
           family = 'gaussian')

gauss2=glm(hypo2,
           data = fromPy,
           family = 'gaussian')

Now let’s take a look at the results:

Both hypotheses are true, as p-value for both of them shows statistical significance. Hypothesis 2 looks like a better model. Let’s confirm it:

anova(gauss1,gauss2,test="Chisq")
## Analysis of Deviance Table
## 
## Model 1: CO2x1000 ~ TotalGDPinMillions
## Model 2: CO2x1000 ~ TotalGDPinMillions + Population

## 2       202 8.5632e+11  1 3.2181e+10 0.005865 **
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

And the R-squared for the second model (hypothesis) is:

library(rsq)
## Warning: package 'rsq' was built under R version 4.1.2
rsq(gauss2,adj=T)
## [1] 0.9178687

R-squared is 0.91, which means that 91% of the variation in our dependent variable (CO2 emissions) is explained by our model.

Let’s plot it:

plot(gauss2,1)

Normality of residuals:

plot(gauss2,2)

plot(gauss2, 3)
